Section A — Your role + company context
Interviewer: What is your current job role or title?
Participant P01: I work as a Senior Operations Officer at Nabil Bank Limited. My role mainly involves managing internal banking processes, coordinating between departments, and supporting branch operations to make sure everything runs smoothly.
Interviewer: What industry is your company in?
Participant P01: Banking and financial services, mainly focused on retail and corporate banking.
Interviewer: Roughly how big is the company?
Participant P01: It’s a large organization with over 1,000 employees, and it has branches across different parts of Nepal.

Section B — Work + recent onboarding
Interviewer: Think about the last time you started a job or changed teams. What did the first few weeks look like?
Participant P01: When I joined the operations team, the first few weeks were quite intense. I had to go through a lot of documents, attend training sessions, and understand different systems and workflows. There were also many meetings, so it felt a bit overwhelming at times.
Interviewer: In the first two weeks, what were the top 3 things you needed to know to do your job well?
Participant P01:
- Understanding how the internal banking systems work in daily operations
- Learning compliance and risk management policies
- Knowing the right people or teams to contact for approvals and support
Interviewer: What was the hardest part of getting started?
Participant P01: The hardest part was finding the right information quickly. Even though the information existed somewhere, it was spread across different platforms, which made it time-consuming to locate.
Interviewer: Did onboarding feel helpful or more like box-ticking?
Participant P01: It was a mix. Some training sessions were useful and relevant, especially system training, but other parts felt more like general onboarding that wasn’t directly related to my role.

Section C — Finding information at work
Interviewer: When you need an answer at work, where do you go first?
Participant P01: Usually I check Microsoft Teams or look through email threads first. If I still don’t find it, I go to our internal document portal or shared folders.
Interviewer: How often do you have to check more than one place?
Participant P01: Very often — almost every day. It’s rare to find everything in one place.
Interviewer: What’s annoying about that?
Participant P01: The main issue is that there are multiple versions of documents. Sometimes you’re not sure which one is the latest, so you spend extra time verifying it.
Interviewer: Tell me about a time you couldn't find something important.
Participant P01: There was a time I needed an updated compliance guideline. I searched in several folders and emails but couldn’t find the latest version. In the end, I had to ask a colleague, which delayed my work by a few hours.
Interviewer: How do you personally keep track of important links or documents?
Participant P01: I usually bookmark important links and save messages in Teams. Sometimes I also keep notes for quick reference.
Interviewer: What's not great about that method?
Participant P01: Over time it becomes disorganized. It’s hard to manage everything, and sometimes I forget where I saved certain things.
Interviewer: If you had one home screen at work, what would you want it to show?
Participant P01: I would want it to show my daily tasks, important announcements, key documents, team contacts, and deadlines. Basically, everything I need to start my day efficiently.
Interviewer: What information should be super quick to reach?
Participant P01: HR policies, IT support contacts, compliance rules, and process guidelines should be easily accessible within a few clicks.
Interviewer: When you find a document, how do you know it’s correct?
Participant P01: I usually check who uploaded it and when it was last updated. If it comes from a manager or official source, I trust it more.

Section D — Starting a job
Interviewer: On your first day, what would have made you feel less lost?
Participant P01: A clear roadmap or step-by-step guide would have helped a lot. It would make it easier to understand what to focus on first instead of figuring everything out on my own.
Interviewer: In your first week, did you clearly know what to do next?
Participant P01: Not really. There were times when I wasn’t sure what my next priority should be, so I had to ask others frequently.
Interviewer: What makes onboarding feel personal and useful?
Participant P01: When the training is tailored to your specific role and responsibilities, it feels much more useful compared to general onboarding sessions.
Interviewer: What made you feel like you were on track?
Participant P01: Getting feedback from my manager and completing assigned tasks or training milestones gave me a sense of progress.
Interviewer: When you needed help, did you know who to ask?
Participant P01: Eventually yes, but in the beginning it wasn’t very clear, so I had to figure it out by asking different people.

Section E — AI helper trust
Interviewer: Have you used AI tools at work?
Participant P01: Yes, I’ve used AI tools mainly for searching documents and summarizing information, which helps save time.
Interviewer: What would make you trust an AI answer?
Participant P01: I would trust it more if it shows the source of the information, like linking to the original document or policy.
Interviewer: What would make you not trust it?
Participant P01: If the answer is vague, incomplete, or outdated, then I wouldn’t rely on it.
Interviewer: What questions should AI redirect to a human?
Participant P01: Sensitive topics like HR issues, promotions, or policy decisions should be handled by a human instead of AI.
Interviewer: Would you worry about privacy?
Participant P01: Yes, especially if the AI is using internal company data or employee information. I would want assurance that the data is secure.

Section F — Wrap-up
Interviewer: What were the top 2 problems you mentioned today?
Participant P01:
- Difficulty finding correct information quickly
- Having to use multiple platforms for the same task
Interviewer: What do those problems cost you?
Participant P01: They cost time, reduce productivity, and sometimes lead to mistakes or delays in completing work.
Interviewer: If you could change one thing to make starting a job easier?
Participant P01: I would create a single platform that combines onboarding guidance with verified and up-to-date knowledge, so everything is in one place.
